    "texts": [
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Identification features",
            "shortText": "<p>Upright, evergreen, perennial shrub with elongate, lance-like, lush-green leaves that emerge opposite one another all the way up the multiple erect stems. Both stems and leaves have small white hairs, giving them a velvety feel. Large, showy, bright pink flowers form at the tips of the stems in summer, usually in clusters. Each flower has five broad, glossy petals that are slightly sticky and these surround a prominent group of bright-yellow, twisted anthers.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_1_9658",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Adult size",
            "shortText": "<p>Grows to about 60-80 cm height. Flowers about 35 mm across.&nbsp;</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_2_9659",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Distribution",
            "shortText": "<p><u>Global:</u> Endemic to South Africa.</p><p><u>Local/Regional:</u> Lambert’s Bay to George.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_3_9660",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Biology",
            "shortText": "<p>Hardy plant able to grow very close to the sea and to cope with strong winds, brackish soil and salt spray. The flowers are adapted to pollination by carpenter bees and release their pollen only in response to the vibration of the bees’ wings – a phenomenon known as buzz pollination!</p><p>Useful as an ornamental plant in coastal gardens.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_4_9661",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Food / prey",
            "shortText": "<p>Photosynthetic.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_5_9662",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Reproduction",
            "shortText": "<p>Flowers November - February. Produces fruit capsules (rather than the berries found in many other members of this family) that split along lines of the septa to release numerous small seeds.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_6_9663",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Similar species",
            "shortText": "<p>Distinctive and the only species in the genus. The Christmas berry <i>Chironia baccifera</i> also has bright pink flowers with yellow anthers, but has smaller, slender leaves and produces fruit that are bright red berries.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_7_9664",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        }
    ],
